      "side": 1,
      "message": "I feel like most of this is fine, but since we\u0027ve got a tabula rasa, we might want to try a few new things.  My first thought is, might be neat to provide a constructor like this?\n\n    constexpr SkM4(const float (\u0026x)[4],\n                   const float (\u0026y)[4],\n                   const float (\u0026z)[4],\n                   const float (\u0026w)[4])\n        : fMat{{x[0],x[1],x[2],x[3]},\n               {y[0],y[1],y[2],y[3]},\n               {z[0],z[1],z[2],z[3]},\n               {w[0],w[1],w[2],w[3]}} {}\n\nThat\u0027d let you write, e.g.\n\n    SkM4 foo \u003d {{4,3,2,1},\n                {1,2,3,4},\n                {4,0,0,7},\n                {0,0,0,0}};\n\nand that probably removes the need for the other \"here\u0027s 16 things\" constructors and setters?",
      "revId": "613f4c64c24069bd5b9a7ed23cc08a6f0485deec",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "dd983cfd_13012171",
        "filename": "include/core/SkM4.h",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 25,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-01-03T01:29:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think having these copiers default and inline is actually subtly very powerful.  It might mean we don\u0027t really need almost any setters, instead mostly just defining methods that return new matrices?  A lot of what I\u0027m about to write is going to be conditioned on copying these being cheap, perhaps noops.\n\nGetting boring things like setters out of the API might help make more interesting methods stand out, like the various performance specializations of concat like preTranslate()...postScale().",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 24,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 25,
        "endChar": 47
      },
      "revId": "613f4c64c24069bd5b9a7ed23cc08a6f0485deec",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
